title: MRTpostInfLASSO
text: Micro-randomized trials (MRTs) designed evaluate effectiveness mobile health (mHealth) interventions delivered via smartphones. practice, assumptions required MRTs often difficult satisfy: randomization probabilities can uncertain, observations frequently incomplete, prespecifying features high-dimensional contexts linear working models also challenging. address issues, doubly robust weighted centered least squares (DR-WCLS) framework provides flexible procedure variable selection inference. methods incorporates supervised learning algorithms enables valid inference time-varying causal effects longitudinal settings. vignette introduces MRTpostInfLASSO package. core function, DR_WCLS_LASSO, allows users perform variable selection, estimate time-varying causal effects make valid inferences conditional selected variables. Individual-level data MRT can summarized \(\left\{O_1, A_1, O_2, A_2, \cdots, O_T, A_T, O_{T+1} \right\}\) \(T\) total decision times, \(O_t\) information collected \(t-1\) \(t\), \(A_t\) treatment provided time \(t\). consider treatment \(A_t \\left\{0,1\right\}\). Treatment options intended influence proximal outcome \(Y_{t+1} \O_{t+1}\). Denote history \(H_t = \left\{ O_1, A_1, O_2, A_2, \cdots, A_{t-1}, O_t \right\}\) randomized probabilities \(\mathbf{p} = \left\{p_t(A_t \mid H_t) \right\}_{t=1}^T\). DR-WCLS criterion given \[ \mathbb{P}_n \Bigl[ \sum_{t=1}^{T}   \tilde{\sigma}^2_t(S_t)\,   \Bigl(   \frac{W_t(A_t-\tilde{p}_t(1 \mid S_t)) (Y_{t+1}-g_t(H_t,A_t))}{\tilde{\sigma}^2_t(S_t)}\,   +\beta(t;H_t)-f_t(S_t)^T \beta\Bigr)\,   f_t(S_t) \Bigr] = 0 \] \(\beta(t;H_t) := g_t(H_t,1) - g_t(H_t,0)\) causal excursion effect fully observed history \(H_t\), \(\tilde{\sigma}^2_t(S_t) := \tilde{p}_t(1 \mid S_t)(1-\tilde{p}_t(1 \mid S_t))\). \(\hat{\beta}_n^{(DR)}\) consistent estimator true \(\beta\) either randomization probability \(p_t(A_t \mid H_t)\) conditional expectation \(g_t(H_t, A_t)\) correctly specified. DR_WCLS algorithm follows: Step : Randomly split \(n\) individuals \(K\) equal folds \(\left\{I_k\right\}^K_{k=1}\) assuming \(n\) multiple \(K\). Let \(^∁_k\) denote complement fold k. Step II: fold \(k\), use data \(^∁_k\) estimate nuisance functions \(\hat{g}^{(k)}_t(H_t,A_t)\),\(\hat{p}^{(k)}_t(1 \mid H_t)\), \(\hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_t(1 \mid S_t)\), compute weight \(\hat{W}_t^{(k)} = \hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_t(1 \mid S_t) / \hat{p}^{(k)}_t(1 \mid H_t)\). Step III: \(j \I_k\) time \(t\), construct pseudo-outcome \(\tilde{Y}_{t+1}^{(DR)}\) follows, regress \(f_t(S_t)^T \beta\) using weights \(\tilde{p}_t^{(k)}(1 \mid S_t)(1-\tilde{p}_t^{(k)}(1 \mid S_t))\). \[ \tilde{Y}^{(DR)}_{t+1,j} := \frac{\hat{W}_{t,j}^{(k)}(A_{t,j}-\hat{\tilde{p}}_t^{(k)}(1 \mid S_{t,j})) (Y_{t+1,j}-\hat{g}_t^{(k)}(H_{t,j},A_{t,j}))}{\hat{\tilde{p}}_t^{(k)}(1 \mid S_{t,j})(1-\hat{\tilde{p}}_t^{(k)}(1 \mid S_{t,j}))} \, + \Bigl( \hat{g}_t^{(k)}(H_{t,j},1) - \hat{g}_t^{(k)}(H_{t,j},0) \Bigr) \] conduct variable selection, DR_WCLS_LASSO solves problem \[ \min_{\beta} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{=1}^{n}\sum_{t=1}^{T} \Bigl[   \hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\,   \bigl(1-\hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\bigr)\,   \bigl(\tilde{Y}^{(DR)}_{t+1,}-f_t(S_t)^{\top}\beta\bigr)^2 \Bigr] + \lambda \lVert \beta \rVert_{1} - w^{\top}\beta, \] \(\lambda\) LASSO regularization parameter, \(\omega\) noise vector. variable selection procedure, conduct post-selection inference using DR-WCLS conditional selected variables. provides estimates selected variables along corresponding confidence intervals. \[ \min_{\beta} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{=1}^{n}\sum_{t=1}^{T} \Bigl[   \hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\,   \bigl(1-\hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\bigr)\,   \bigl(\tilde{Y}^{(DR)}_{t+1,}-f_t(S_t)^{\top}\beta_E\bigr)^2 \Bigr] \]

title: MRTpostInfLASSO
text: illustrate functions MRTpostInfLASSO package using HeartSteps dataset MRTAnalysis package. demonstrate generate pseudo-outcome, perform variable selection, conduct valid post-selection inference. HeartSteps mobile health intervention designed encourage physical activity delivering tailored suggestions. dataset comes 6-week micro-randomized trial involving 37 participants. Participants randomized 5 decision points per day received 2-5 notificaitons daily. dataset contains 7,770 records, 5 observations per day participants. record includes decision point, whether notification sent, participant availability walking, 30-minute step counts decision point. begin, load HeartSteps data using following code. summary data_mimicHeartSteps follows: first specify variable names participant ID, history\(H_t\), moderator\(S_t\), treatment\(A_t\), proximal outcome\(Y_t\), randomization probability\(p_t\).
code: # Load HeartSteps Data library(MRTAnalysis) data(data_mimicHeartSteps) head(data_mimicHeartSteps) #>   userid decision_point day_in_study logstep_30min logstep_30min_lag1 #> 1      1              1            0     2.3902011          0.0000000 #> 2      1              2            0    -0.6931472          2.3902011 #> 3      1              3            0     2.4646823         -0.6931472 #> 4      1              4            0     0.1206936          2.4646823 #> 5      1              5            0     0.8322060          0.1206936 #> 6      1              6            1     1.8450452          0.8322060 #>   logstep_pre30min is_at_home_or_work intervention rand_prob avail #> 1       -0.6931472                  1            0       0.6     0 #> 2        2.1962380                  1            0       0.6     1 #> 3        4.5894007                  1            1       0.6     1 #> 4        3.1791124                  1            1       0.6     1 #> 5        3.2945170                  0            0       0.6     0 #> 6        4.6658254                  1            0       0.6     0 set.seed(100) ID = 'userid' Ht = c('logstep_30min_lag1','logstep_pre30min','is_at_home_or_work', 'day_in_study') St = c('logstep_30min_lag1','logstep_pre30min','is_at_home_or_work', 'day_in_study') At = 'intervention' outcome = 'logstep_30min' prob = 'rand_prob'

title: MRTpostInfLASSO
text: perform variable selection, DR_WCLS_LASSO solves problem \[ \min_{\beta} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{=1}^{n}\sum_{t=1}^{T} \Bigl[   \hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\,   \bigl(1-\hat{\tilde{p}}^{(k)}_{t}(1 \mid S_t)\bigr)\,   \bigl(\tilde{Y}^{(DR)}_{t+1,}-f_t(S_t)^{\top}\beta\bigr)^2 \Bigr] + \lambda \lVert \beta \rVert_{1} - w^{\top}\beta \] Variable selection performed using variable_selection_PY_penal_int FISTA_backtracking function. first define my_formula, specifying outcome candidate variables. , demonstrate use functions. Python version R version
code: my_formula = as.formula(paste("yDR ~", paste(c("logstep_30min_lag1", "logstep_pre30min",                                       "is_at_home_or_work", "day_in_study"),                                        collapse = " + ")))  set.seed(100) var_selection_python = variable_selection_PY(data = pseudo_outcome_CVlasso,ID,                                              my_formula,                                              lam = NULL, noise_scale = NULL,                                              venv = venv,                                              splitrat = 0.8,                                              beta = NULL)  cat('The selected variable list:',var_selection_python$E) #> The selected variable list: (Intercept) day_in_study set.seed(100) var_selection_R = FISTA_backtracking(data = pseudo_outcome_CVlasso, ID, my_formula,                   lam = NULL, noise_scale = NULL,splitrat = 0.8,                   max_ite = 10^(5), tol = 10^(-4), beta = NULL) var_selection_R$E #> [1] "(Intercept)"  "day_in_study"  cat('The selected variable list:',var_selection_R$E) #> The selected variable list: (Intercept) day_in_study

title: MRTpostInfLASSO

title: Post-Selection Inference for MRTs
text: Micro-randomized trials (MRTs) designed evaluate effectiveness mobile health (mHealth) interventions delivered via smartphones. practice, assumptions required MRTs often difficult satisfy: randomization probabilities can uncertain, observations frequently incomplete, prespecifying features high-dimensional contexts linear working models also challenging. address issues, doubly robust weighted centered least squares (DR-WCLS) framework provides flexible procedure variable selection inference. methods incorporates supervised learning algorithms enables valid inference time-varying causal effects longitudinal settings.
